<NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">Four or five</NUMEX> private <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">schools</ENAMEX> did contact the school district to express
interest in the program, but all considered a payment of <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$3,600</NUMEX> too low.
Tuition at run-of-the-mill private <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">schools</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Houston</ENAMEX> runs more like <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">$5,500</NUMEX> for
the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">school year</TIMEX>. At elite academies, it can be <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">as much as $12,000</NUMEX> per year.
Since the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Chronicle</ENAMEX> story was published, one
private <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">school</ENAMEX> has agreed to accept <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">25</NUMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">students</ENAMEX>. It's a mostly <ENAMEX TYPE="NATIONALITY">African-American</ENAMEX>
